    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, you're right, I'm sorry! I got carried away with the goblin lore and forgot to give you the straight business advice you actually need.\n\nA low inventory turnover ratio in your clothing shop usually means you are **overstocking** or **under-selling**.\n\nHere are the actual business reasons why this happens:\n\n1.  **Slow Sales Velocity**: You might have bought a lot of trendy items that aren't selling fast enough. The money is tied up in unsold stock, meaning you aren't generating cash flow.\n2.  **Poor Forecasting**: You may have guessed wrong about what customers want. If you ordered too many of a specific style that isn't popular, you end up with dead inventory.\n3.  **Seasonal Mismatch**: You might have bought winter coats in the summer, or summer dresses in the winter, leading to items sitting in your closet that can't be sold.\n4.  **High Return Rates**: If customers return clothes frequently, your effective inventory cost goes up, and the turnover rate drops because you're constantly restocking items that are being sent back.\n\nTo fix it, you need to analyze your sales data to see which items are moving slowly and",
